HAPPY FRIDAY TO EVERYONE except the coaches who are setting their clients up for unsustainable eating and gate keeping how to actually eat for their goals and create balanced, effective change.

It blows my mind how many people I talk to who tell me they’re working with “@fitbabe42” and they’re eating 1100 calories, doing 45 minutes of cardio and eating a lemon with a side of chicken. (Sorry @fitbabe42, your username is just an example).

I’m overrrrrr it.

Unless you are being coached by a professional to compete in a body building competition OR you’ve recently gone through gastric bypass surgery - in most circumstances, your calories should NOT be 800-1200cal.

I’m telling you this because I NEED you to trust that calories are not bad and carbs and fats will not make you fat. 

Please don’t be fooled by your favorite Instagram fitness influencer who has abs and a nice butt. They’re not eating 1200 calories either. Please don’t fall for the quick fixes with coaches who aren’t qualified to be coaches.

So happy Friday, to everyone. Except these people.

If you’re down to learn how to fuel your body for workouts, what to do in the gym, and truly understand what kind of nutrition your body needs - fill out the link in my bio and let’s talk.

I’m tired of the fakes. Let’s get you to understand what you’re eating and why.

If you’re struggling to hit your protein numbers, please don’t be discouraged and stop all together.

Intentional effort to increase your protein by small amounts at first will add up over time. One more ounce of chicken, a full meal rather than a snack, a protein shake after a workout. 

It doesn’t have to be perfect, just 1% better every day.
 
#protein #healthymeals #highprotein #fitness #fatloss #muscle #bettereveryday

“It gets easier, right?”

I’ve been hearing this question a lot in the past week or so as I have new clients starting their programming with me, new members trying CrossFit or F45 for the first time.

The answer is no. It doesn’t get easier. You get better. Your threshold for effort becomes higher as you get stronger, faster and your endurance increases. You continue to set new standards of hard work and from there, your ability to push through becomes less questionable. It’s not a matter of IF you’ll finish a workout, it’s a matter of HOW are you going to get it done?

My favorite thing about coaching is witnessing the increased confidence of my clients and those around me. Whether that confidence is in new movements at the gym, their endurance or their clothes and simply - their skin.

I encourage you to look at how far you’ve come. Where was your effort, confidence and ability to push when you first started and where is it now?

You’re a badass. Own it. 🫶🏼
Stay in your lane. Protect your energy. Get sh*t done.

Just because I coach people to workout, eat well and move, doesn’t mean that it’s easy for me to show up. I do it because it’s good for my body, it’s excellent for my mental health and it’s great to be a solid example. But sometimes — MOST times, it’s hard. And I don’t want to. 

Don't let your lazy mind win today. Mine almost did. Get into some clothes you can move in, put your shoes on and get out the door 🤘🏼

If you’re tired of mediocre results, put more effort into what will make you better.

➡️move more
➡️lift heavier
➡️recover intentionally

Whatever it is, get it done.

When you nail down your why, the chances you’ll execute  becomes more probable because you give a shit.

➡️ get clear on what you want
➡️ figure out what will have to change in your current lifestyle to get there
➡️ be honest about if you are willing to do those things

If yes - awesome, go get it.
If no - change your expectations around what are goals are or what your timeline is 
If you have no idea - let’s talk about it 🫶🏼

2023 Murph workout complete ✅

Plantar fasciitis has taken me out of running, but the @concept2inc rower helped me get the job done.

If you’ve never done this workout, or heard of it — “Murph” is done annually on Memorial Day (or MDW) by athletes (if you have a body, you’re an athlete) all over the world to honor Navy LT Michael Murphy who was killed in Afghanistan in 2005.

The workout as prescribed is:
1 mile run
100 pull ups
200 push ups
300 squats
1 mile run
all while wearing a 20lb vest.

If that seems tough for you, scale whatever way necessary. Half the distance, row or bike, half the reps, incline push ups, ring or TRX rows in place of pull ups, sit ups instead of squats or push ups. Partition the reps however you need. Just get something done. 

I encourage you to try it and if you plan on doing it this weekend, have already done it, or anticipate giving it a go — write it in the comments or share with me in my DMs. If you’re not sure how much to bite off, let me help and we can strategize a way to break it down.

Nothing will change if you choose to stay the same.

It’s easy to fall victim to our excuses. We don’t have enough time. We’re tired after work. We can’t get out of bed early enough. We have too many things to do around the house.

If you’re constantly telling yourself any of the above, your excuses hold priority over your health.

Make movement a non negotiable. Arrange  better food choices. Get to bed earlier. Drink more water. Be mindful of who you surround yourself with.

Move your a*s and start making changes.
Your body and your mind will thank you.

5 small things - that feel like BIG things - that don’t define who you are.

1 & 2: Your weight is just a number. Your clothing size is also just a number. Comparing these to other people or even where you used to be, is a recipe for mental disaster. Be where your feet are and measure your physical successes off of what your body can do, not how much it weighs or what it fits into.

3: What other people think of you is none of your business. 

4: mistakes happen, sometimes we make decisions that lead to regret. sh*t happens. Don’t let mistakes get the best of you - learn, pivot and grow from these. Mistakes = opportunity.

5: Weaknesses won’t always be weaknesses. Start looking at what you’re not good at as work in progress rather than neglecting them. Spend time improving these things rather than feeling sorry for where you currently are. You are never stuck, you are never weak. Weakness is a mentality.

For the last 7 years I have had the privilege of coaching both men and women kick unwanted habits around nutrition, exercise and their mindset.

What you eat and how you move are both extremely important components to a healthy life, but what you tell yourself you’re capable or incapable of will shape your outcome. 

“whether you think you can or you think you can’t — you’re right.” 

I talk to people DAILY about what is getting in the way of them seeing the results they want. Rarely they answer, “me.” And most often, the correct answer is themselves. 

When you choose to embrace what you CAN do, you will change. Opportunity will arise where you once thought you lacked, and you’ll be free from limitation and self doubt. Get out of your own way and stop thinking you can’t. Or you’ll fail. Or you’ll never stick with it. Or it’s never worked for you. If you continue to tell yourself you are the victim, you always will be.

Adopt the right outlook, be patient and trust the process — there is no such thing as failure.

Friendly reminder that not everything you see on social media is real.

This platform is a space where most people show their best and very little of their worst. Your favorite fitness influencer still gets bloated, probably doesn’t have a shredded six pack at all hours of the day and most likely has some cellulite, whether they choose to show it off or not. 

Don’t be fooled — but most importantly, don’t let social media’s fake reality allow you to believe that “skinnier” or “fitter” are synonymous with “happier.”

I knowwww protein can be struggle for some, but I truly love this question. I really enjoy brainstorming with my clients, people at the gym, or friends, to figure out what kind of protein sources they LIKE to eat and how they can get more of it.

First off - quantity of protein needed in grams depends on you and your goals, but a good place to start is somewhere around .7-.8x your body weight in lbs at a minimum. So for example, if you weigh 200lbs, you should be getting at least 140g/160g of protein in every day.

If you have no idea how much that is in terms of quantity, weigh out your food and track it - @myfitnesspal is a user friendly app to start somewhere.

Now for the protein sources. Here’s a simple list of some foods you can begin to incorporate if you’re not already. And if you are already - try a bigger serving size. Instead of 3oz of ground turkey, have 5-6oz! 

• ground beef - I typically use 93/7 lean
• chicken - breast, thighs, rotisserie, whatever you want.
• steak - sirloins and rounds are good leaner options, but regardless of the cut and contrary to what is said about red meat - it’s good for you. Eat it if you like it, don’t if you hate it. 
• salmon/ tilapia/ tuna/ cod/ rockfish/ mahi-mahi - whatever kind of fish you prefer.
• bacon/ turkey bacon
• eggs, egg whites, liquid egg whites
• ground turkey
• plain non fat Greek yogurt
• protein powders 
• Oikos pro yogurt/ ratio yogurt
• the better bagel bagels
• banza pasta/ protein pasta
• Kodiak pancakes/ waffles

Towards the end we get into less “whole food” options, but as long as you are not reliant on protein supplements and processed protein chips, snacks, waffles, etc. - have them.

Find ways that you enjoy these foods above. They don’t have to be 99% lean or tasteless, lacking seasonings and sauces. 

The more you like it, the more willing you’ll be to eat it, the more sustainable a high protein diet becomes, the more results you’ll see 👏🏼

It’s been a while since I’ve introduced myself.

For those of you who are new here, HI! 👋🏼 my name is Emily MacDonnell. I am a nutrition and fitness coach, primarily serving my clients virtually (this means, yes, we can work together even if you live across the country or the world 🌎🤩)

I put my nutrition degree, multiple fitness certifications and internships to use and started my business, @empowercoaching_ in 2017. 

At the time, I was working in the nutrition space and was noticing how many fitness fanatics were completely lost in the kitchen and weren’t seeing any results. There were others who could notttt find a way to incorporate workouts into their schedules. And there were some people I came across who didn’t have nutrition or exercise locked in - yet. 

My goal was, and still is, to bridge the gap between exercise and nutrition. I teach my clients better habits and prioritization, and explain that being healthy doesn’t have to be complicated. They also don’t have to give up their favorite foods or do things they don’t enjoy. 

What I love most about what I do is having the opportunity to help enhance the lives of others. Watching someone who juggles work, kids, relationships, and overlapping schedules, work their a** off and flourish into a confident powerhouse is unlike anything else.

Whether you’re my client, friend, or social media acquaintance, I’m down to support you any way that I can. So don’t be shy, say hey,  and ask questions if you have ‘em! 🫶🏼⚡️ 

If you’re interested in being coached by me, fill out the application in my bio and book a free consultation call with me so I can see if and how I can help!

In hindsight, all of it is my story. I can’t change it, nor do I wish to. My sobriety is not my identity, but it is something I value, a big part of who I am, and continue to grow to be.

The most mentally challenging workout I’ve ever done. this is my second time completing “Chad” (1,000 box step ups with a 40# ruck - I chose 20#) in honor of Veteran’s Day and Chad Wilkinson, a Navy SEAL, serving for 21 years, who took his own life in 2018. 

This workout is a way to pay respect to Chad, veterans, those who have lost their lives or a loved one to suicide, and to raise awareness for suicide prevention. Mental health diseases are silent, do not discriminate, and something that even the strongest fall to. 

At 200 reps, I thought about stopping.
At 500, I considered taking my vest off.
At 700, I wanted to quit. 
At 800, I didn’t think I’d finish.
At 930, I was ready to be done.

The reps in between, I thought about the pain I was feeling and how the pain of PTSD, depression, loneliness, helplessness and hopelessness weighs so much f*cking more than the 20lbs I had on my back.

If you choose to try this workout today or tomorrow, get mentally tough and remember why you’re doing it. Be apart of something bigger than yourself. And if you are struggling to know that you deserve to live on this earth, here is your reminder that you do 🤍

Options to modify:
•body weight with smaller step up height
•less total step up count (300,500,750,800 etc.)

3 things I would implement if I wanted to prioritize my health. Save this or send it to the person who will keep you accountable! 

01. Focus on one thing, one week at a time.

Walking, sleep, protein, water, fruits, vegetables, whole food,  healthy fats, complex carbs, supportive friends, family or community. Focus on one and the rest become a bonus. 

In a fitness world where the underlying product pitch is restriction, focus on adding more of some of the above. While going 0-100 works for some people, sustainability often lacks. Pick ONE thing from the list and make that your sole focus for the next week or two. When you feel like you’ve been doing a really great job at getting 100oz of water or 3-4 servings of vegetables, move onto another! 

02. Set three daily non negotiable tasks.

I like the open check box method - but the idea behind this is to write down 3 things that need to get done that day. Maybe it’s a workout, maybe it’s your water intake, maybe it’s something at work that has nothing to do with fitness. This will set you up for success by instilling prioritization in your daily life. Make sure this does not become your to do list. Only 3 tasks at highest priority before your head hits the pillow. *hint: these are typically things you don’t want to do 👀

03. Get prepared.

Set your clothes out for your workout the night before, or pack them if you plan on getting it done after work. Have food cooked or available for high quality meals when you need them. Prioritize your sleep every night - better sleep = better nutritional decisions, less fatigue and better workouts. Make sure to take in more protein. High protein = more sustained energy and higher satiety. If you plan your meals with more protein, you will stay more full for a longer period of time — eliminating the 3 o’clock snacking or ravenous eating before or at dinner.
